<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Audit-related fees comprise fees for professional services that are reasonably related to the performance of the worldwide audit or review of the Company&#146;s
financial statements. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(3)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Tax fees relate to professional services rendered in connection with tax audits, international tax compliance, and international tax consulting and planning services.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Policy on Audit Committee Pre-Approval of Audit and Non-Audit Services Performed by the Independent Registered Public
Accounting Firm </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company maintains an auditor independence policy that bans its auditors from performing non-financial
consulting services, such as information technology consulting and internal audit services. This policy mandates that the Audit Committee approve the audit and non-audit services and related budget in advance, and that the Audit Committee be
provided with quarterly reporting on actual spending. This policy also mandates that the Company may not enter into auditor engagements for non-audit services without the express approval of the Audit Committee. In accordance with this policy, the
Audit Committee pre-approved all services to be performed by the Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Vote
Required </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposal No.&nbsp;2 requires the affirmative vote of (i)&nbsp;a majority of the shares present or
represented by proxy and voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;a majority of the shares required to constitute the quorum. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board recommends a vote FOR Proposal No.&nbsp;2. </B></FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">39 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>PROPOSAL NO. 3 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Advisory Vote on Executive Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company is providing its
shareholders with the opportunity to cast an advisory vote on executive compensation (a &#147;<I>say-on-pay-proposal</I>&#148;) as described below. The Company believes that it is appropriate to seek the views of shareholders on the design and
effectiveness of the Company&#146;s executive compensation program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">At the Company&#146;s annual meeting of shareholders held
in February 2011, a substantial majority of the votes cast on the say-on-pay proposal were voted in favor of the proposal. The Compensation Committee believes this affirms shareholders&#146; support of the Company&#146;s approach to executive
compensation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s goal for its executive compensation program is to attract, motivate, and retain a talented,
entrepreneurial and creative team of executives who will provide leadership for the Company&#146;s success in dynamic and competitive markets. The Company seeks to accomplish this goal in a way that rewards performance and is aligned with its
shareholders&#146; long-term interests. The Company believes that its executive compensation program, which emphasizes long-term equity awards, satisfies this goal and is strongly aligned with the long-term interests of its shareholders. The
Company&#146;s total shareholder return over the prior 1-, 3- and 5-year periods was 34%, 235% and 395%, respectively. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Compensation Discussion and Analysis, beginning on page&nbsp;21 of this Proxy Statement, describes the Company&#146;s executive compensation program and the decisions made by the Compensation Committee in 2011 in more detail. Important
considerations for the 2011 program include the following: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Jobs, the Company&#146;s former CEO, passed away on October&nbsp;5, 2011. Mr.&nbsp;Jobs had resigned as the Company&#146;s CEO on
August&nbsp;24, 2011, and, on the same date, the Board appointed Mr.&nbsp;Cook as CEO. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with Mr.&nbsp;Cook&#146;s appointment as CEO, the Board granted Mr.&nbsp;Cook 1,000,000 RSUs as a promotion and retention award. The
Board views Mr.&nbsp;Cook&#146;s retention as CEO as critical to the Company&#146;s success and smooth leadership transition. Accordingly, 50% of Mr.&nbsp;Cook&#146;s award is scheduled to vest on August&nbsp;24, 2016 (five years after the award
date) and 50% of Mr.&nbsp;Cook&#146;s award is scheduled to vest on August&nbsp;24, 2021 (ten years after the award date), subject to Mr.&nbsp;Cook&#146;s continued employment with the Company through the applicable vesting date. The RSU award is
intended as a long-term retention incentive for Mr.&nbsp;Cook, and, accordingly, should be viewed as compensation over the 10-year vesting period and not solely as compensation for 2011. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">RSUs constitute the majority of each named executive officer&#146;s total compensation opportunity. The Company believes these awards ensure that a
significant portion of the officers&#146; compensation is tied to long-term stock price performance. Beginning in 2011, all of the Company&#146;s RSU awards are subject to &#147;recoupment&#148; provisions, which provide that the award may be
recovered under certain circumstances. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Cash compensation (base salary and annual performance-based cash bonus award) levels for the named executive officers are below the levels generally
provided by peer companies. The Company has no long-term cash compensation program for its named executive officers, nor does it have a pension plan. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">None of the named executive officers has an employment agreement or severance arrangement. In addition, the Company generally does not provide any
perquisites, tax reimbursements, or change in control benefits to the named executive officers that are not available to other employees. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of the named executive officers is employed at will and is expected to demonstrate exceptional personal performance in order to continue serving
as a member of the executive team. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">40 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company believes the compensation program for the named executive officers is
instrumental in helping the Company achieve its strong financial performance. In addition to the 1-, 3- and 5-year performance of the Company&#146;s stock noted above, in 2011, the Company&#146;s revenue grew to $108.2 billion, representing an
increase of $43.0 billion or 66% over the prior year. Net income grew to $25.9 billion in 2011, an increase of $11.9 billion or 85% over the prior year. The Company&#146;s strong earnings and operational performance helped drive a cash and
marketable securities balance of $81.6 billion at the end of 2011, an increase of $30.6 billion over the prior year-end. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Company requests shareholder approval of the compensation of the Company&#146;s named executive officers as disclosed pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules (which disclosure includes the Compensation Discussion and Analysis, the
compensation tables, and the narrative disclosures that accompany the compensation tables). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As an advisory vote, this
proposal is not binding upon the Company. However, the Compensation Committee, which is responsible for designing and administering the Company&#146;s executive compensation program, values the opinions expressed by shareholders in their vote on
this proposal, and will continue to consider the outcome of the vote when making future compensation decisions and policies regarding named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Vote Required </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposal No.&nbsp;3 requires the affirmative
vote of (i)&nbsp;a majority of the shares present or represented by proxy and voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;a majority of the shares required to constitute the quorum. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board recommends a vote FOR Proposal
No.&nbsp;3. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>PROPOSAL NO. 4 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Shareholder Proposal Entitled &#147;Conflict of Interest Report&#148; </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Company has been advised that The National Center for Public Policy Research, 501 Capitol Court, N.E., Suite 200, Washington, District of Columbia 20002, a beneficial owner of the Company&#146;s common stock having a market value in excess of
$2,000, intends to submit the proposal set forth below at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>RESOLVED</B>: Shareholders request the Board
of Directors complete a report by November 2012 to shareholders, prepared at reasonable cost and omitting proprietary information, on board compliance with Apple&#146;s Business Conduct Policy. The report should: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">1.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Disclose the investments of board members that could reasonably be viewed as a financial conflict of interest; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Describe the role board members play in the development of the Company&#146;s policies and the process by which Apple determines if board member participation violates
its Business Conduct Policy; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">3.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Disclose policies that could financially benefit board members. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">41 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>SUPPORTING STATEMENT: </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As shareholders, we support transparency and accountability regarding the Company&#146;s board of directors. Absent a
system of accountability, Company assets could be used to support objectives not in the Company&#146;s best interest. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We are concerned that Apple&#146;s policy on greenhouse gas regulations was developed to personally benefit a board member in violation of the Company&#146;s Business Conduct Policy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Current disclosure is insufficient to ensure that the board of directors is executing its fiduciary responsibilities to
shareholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Board member Al Gore is an outspoken advocate for regulation of greenhouse gases to address
global warming concerns. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During the contentious political debate over global warming regulations in 2009,
Apple resigned its membership in the U.S. Chamber of Commerce because the group opposed the EPA&#146;s effort to pursue global warming regulations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In a letter to the U.S. Chamber, Apple said, &#147;We strongly object to the Chamber&#146;s recent comments opposing the EPA&#146;s effort to limit greenhouse gases.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">News reports implied Gore played a role in Apple&#146;s decision to leave the group: &#147;By the way, Al Gore is on
Apple&#146;s board, though neither he nor the company would comment on whether he was at all involved in Apple&#146;s decision.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Gore has personal financial interests in companies that would profit from government regulation of greenhouse gases. He is a partner in Kleiner Perkins Caufield&nbsp;&amp; Byers, a venture capital firm
that has made clean energy part of its core investment strategy. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Apple&#146;s Business Conduct Policy defines
a conflict of interest as &#147;...any activity that is inconsistent with or opposed to Apple&#146;s best interests, or that gives the appearance of impropriety or divided loyalty.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Since Apple&#146;s business in computers and electronic devices does not make the Company a major emitter of greenhouse
gases, global warming regulations are not a core business issue for the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">However, global warming
regulations are central to Gore&#146;s personal investments. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Gore&#146;s advocacy for global warming
regulations is controversial and his involvement in Apple&#146;s greenhouse gas policy could harm the company&#146;s reputation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Resigning from the U.S. Chamber could harm Apple&#146;s business interests in other policy matters, such as international trade and intellectual property. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Shareholders have a right to know if Apple&#146;s involvement in greenhouse gas regulations is being driven by
Gore&#146;s personal interests. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Company&#146;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;4 </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;4 </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">42 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company is committed to transparent corporate governance practices and to policies that
promote the accountability of its Board. The Company does not believe that the report advocated in Proposal No.&nbsp;4 is either a necessary or a useful undertaking to foster transparency or accountability at the Board level. The Company already has
a robust set of policies and procedures in place to identify and address conflicts of interest by its directors, and the intent of the proposal is already substantially implemented. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has adopted and vigorously enforces a number of policies that are designed to avoid any actual or potential conflicts of
interest by its directors. The Company has in place a Business Conduct Policy, a Related Party Transactions Policy, and Guidelines Regarding Director Conflicts of Interest, all of which are available on the Company&#146;s website at
www.apple.com/investor. These policies establish comprehensive procedures for ensuring compliance with all applicable laws and regulations and the Company&#146;s values, including avoidance of conflict of interest by its directors. The Conflict of
Interest Guidelines, for example, require each director to promptly notify the Company&#146;s General Counsel of any facts that may suggest an actual or potential conflict of interest. The Nominating and Corporate Governance of the Board then
determines whether such a conflict exists. If the Committee believes one may exist, it has a number of remedies available, including not providing the director in question any information regarding the subject matter involving the conflict of
interest, requiring the director&#146;s recusal from any review or vote on the subject matter of the conflict of interest, submitting a transaction posing a conflict of interest to the approval by the full Board or shareholders, or requiring the
director to resign from the Board. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Related Party Transactions Policy requires directors to notify the Company&#146;s
General Counsel of any potential transaction with the Company in which the director may have a material direct or indirect interest prior to entering into it. The Audit and Finance Committee of the Board then determines whether to approve or
disapprove the Company&#146;s entry into the transaction. Once entered, SEC rules require the Company to publicly disclose the transaction. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The proposal requests the disclosure of policies that could financially benefit members of its Board. The Company does not have policies that are designed to exclusively benefit its Board members.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company resigned from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce more than two years ago and has not seen any impact on its business as
a result. The decision in 2009 did not &#147;harm Apple&#146;s business interests in other policy matters,&#148; nor does the Board believe it will in the future. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The decision to quit the Chamber was not driven by any conflict of interest or undue influence by any member of the Board. The Company resigned its membership because the Chamber&#146;s position on
climate change differed so sharply with the Company&#146;s. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has a long-standing commitment to environmental
responsibility. Every product the Company makes exceeds the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency&#146;s ENERGY STAR guidelines for energy efficiency, and the Company is the only one in its industry that can make this claim. The Company is able to
deliver such exceptional energy efficiency because it designs both the hardware and the software for its products. Through extensive research and development by its remarkably talented engineers, the Company achieves energy efficiency that other
companies simply cannot. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Furthermore, the Company has been a leader in the area of environmental reporting and provides a
comprehensive accounting of its greenhouse gas emissions every year, including the impact of energy consumption by customers using its products. The Company&#146;s website also offers this information on a per-product basis so as to enable its
customers to be better informed when making purchasing decisions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For all of the reasons above, the Board recommends a vote
AGAINST this proposal. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">43 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Vote Required </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposal No.&nbsp;4 requires the affirmative vote of (i)&nbsp;a majority of the shares present or represented by proxy and voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;a majority of the shares
required to constitute the quorum. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;4. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>PROPOSAL NO. 5 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Shareholder Proposal Entitled &#147;Shareholder Say on
Director Pay&#148; </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has been advised that James McRitchie, 9295 Yorkship Court, Elk Grove, California 95758, a
beneficial owner of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock having a market value in excess of $2,000, intends to submit the proposal set forth below at the Annual Meeting. Mr.&nbsp;McRitchie has authorized John Chevedden (or his designee) to act
on his behalf regarding the proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>RESOLVED</B>: Shareholders request that our Board of Directors adopt a policy that
provides shareholders the opportunity, at each annual meeting, to vote on an advisory proposal, prepared by the Board of Directors, to ratify the pay given members of our Board of Directors as disclosed in the proxy statement. The proposal submitted
to shareholders should make clear that the vote is non-binding and would not affect any pay given to any director. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>SUPPORTING STATEMENT: </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The proxy advisory firms Institutional Shareholder Services and Glass Lewis each recommended that shareholders of at least one major company vote in favor of a 2011 shareholder proposal on this topic. A
shareholder proposal with similarities to this proposal won 55%-support at a major company in 2010. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This
proposal is similar to our management&#146;s proposal on this same ballot enabling us to cast a vote in regard to the pay of our executives. This shareholder proposal simply extends the shareholder voting opportunity to apply to our directors. Some
of our directors are paid more than $1 million for work that may take less than 400 hours per year&#151;or $2500-plus per hour. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The merit of this Shareholder Say on Director Pay proposal should be considered in the context of the need for improvements in our company&#146;s 2011 reported corporate governance status: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Only one yes-vote from our 900&nbsp;million shares was all it took to reelect each of our current directors. On the other
hand, we cannot elect a director by written consent to fill a vacancy created by removal except by a 100%-vote from our 900&nbsp;million shares. Two of our directors owned less than 200 shares each, including a member of our Audit committee.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Two of our directors were active CEOs, Andrea Jung and Millard Drexler. CEOs don&#146;t always make the best
directors. While CEOs are on many boards, they don&#146;t always make the best directors, according to a recent survey by Heidrick&nbsp;&amp; Struggles and Stanford University&#146;s Rock Center for Corporate Governance. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Active CEOs were described by some respondents as &#147;too busy with their own companies to be effective
directors.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stephen Miles, a vice chairman at Heidrick&nbsp;&amp; Struggles said, &#147;Because active
CEOs are so busy, they might be unavailable during a crisis or have to cancel meeting attendance at the last minute. They also have </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">44 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
less time to review materials. For some, the demands of their full-time job make it hard for them to consistently be as engaged as they need to be.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Plus these two CEO directors made up two-thirds of our Executive Pay Committee. And Timothy Cook&#146;s pay was $59
million. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Corporate Library www.thecorporatelibrary.com, an independent investment research firm, said our
directors Albert A. Gore Jr. and Millard Drexler were paid more than $1 million each. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The above concerns
shows there is need for improvement. Please encourage our board to respond positively to this proposal: Shareholder Say on Director Pay&#151;Yes on 5.* </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Company&#146;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;5 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;5. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company believes its shareholders have consistently elected
exceptionally qualified directors from diverse business backgrounds. The Company also believes that its director compensation is reasonable and appropriate. Only directors not employed by the Company (&#147;<I>non-employee directors</I>&#148;) are
compensated for their service on the Board. In addition, a substantial portion of the annual compensation for the Company&#146;s non-employee directors is equity-based to further align the interests of the Company&#146;s directors with those of its
shareholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has sound governance practices with respect to its director compensation program. The Compensation
Committee annually reviews the compensation of the Board and committee members and makes recommendations to the Board with respect to the program. As part of this process, the Compensation Committee engages Frederic W. Cook&nbsp;&amp; Co.
(&#147;<I>F.W. Cook</I>&#148;), an independent executive compensation consulting firm, to conduct an independent review of director compensation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">F.W. Cook provides information to the Compensation Committee regarding competitive compensation practices, peer analysis and recommendations with respect to director compensation using the same peer group
identified in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section beginning on page 21 of this Proxy Statement. In 2011, the Compensation Committee determined, using peer company data provided by F.W. Cook, that the Company&#146;s
compensation levels for its non-employee directors were at approximately the 25th percentile of the peer group, in spite of the Company&#146;s larger market capitalization, revenue growth, and net income growth. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to the annual retainers and RSU awards described in this Proxy Statement, the only other compensation routinely provided by
the Company to its non-employee directors is pursuant to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors Equipment Program (the &#147;<I>Equipment Program</I>&#148;). Under the Equipment Program, each non-employee director may receive, free of charge, one of
each new product introduced by the Company and may purchase additional equipment at a discount. The Equipment Program is designed to encourage directors to become familiar with new Apple products. Directors are not provided tax gross-up payments for
the taxable income they incur in connection with the Equipment Program. Over the past four years, the average compensation for each director from the Equipment Program was less than $7,500 per year. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As described elsewhere in this Proxy Statement, the Company&#146;s shareholder returns for the past 1-, 3- and 5-years have been
exceptional under the oversight of the Board and, as noted above, the Company&#146;s compensation levels for its non-employee directors are well within the range for director compensation paid by the peer group companies. It is not clear from the
proposal why the proponent believes that the Company needs the additional, and highly unusual, oversight of a director say-on-pay vote. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Shareholders already have considerable influence over the Board and its policies through their ability to elect the Company&#146;s directors on an annual basis. Moreover, the Company has encouraged and
continues to </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">45 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
encourage shareholders to communicate directly with the Board regarding any concerns about the Company, including compensation of directors. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For all of the reasons above, the Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Vote Required </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval
of Proposal No.&nbsp;5 requires the affirmative vote of (i)&nbsp;a majority of the shares present or represented by proxy and voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;a majority of the shares required to constitute the quorum. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;5. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>PROPOSAL NO. 6
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Shareholder Proposal Entitled &#147;Report on Political Contributions and Expenditures&#148; </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has been advised that Carey Lovelace, 105 Duane St. #40E, New York, New York 10007, a beneficial owner of shares of the
Company&#146;s common stock having a market value in excess of $2,000, intends to submit the proposal set forth below at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>RESOLVED, </B>that the shareholders of Apple Inc. (&#147;Company&#148;) hereby request that the Company provide a report, updated semiannually, disclosing the Company&#146;s: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">1.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Policies and procedures for political contributions and expenditures (both direct and indirect) made with corporate funds. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Monetary and non-monetary contributions and expenditures (direct and indirect) used to participate or intervene in any political campaign on behalf of (or in opposition
to) any candidate for public office, and used in&nbsp;any attempt to influence the general public, or segments thereof, with respect to elections or referenda. The report shall include: </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">a.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">An accounting through an itemized report that includes the identity of the recipient as well as the amount paid to each recipient of the Company&#146;s funds that are
used for political contributions or expenditures as described above; and </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">b.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The title(s) of the person(s) in the Company who participated in making the decisions to make the political contribution or expenditure. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The report shall be presented to the board of directors&#146; audit committee or other relevant oversight committee and posted on the
Company&#146;s website. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>SUPPORTING STATEMENT: </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As long-term shareholders of Apple, we support transparency and accountability in corporate spending on political
activities. These include any activities considered intervention in any political campaign under the Internal Revenue Code, such as direct and indirect political contributions to candidates, political parties, or political organizations; independent
expenditures; or electioneering communications on behalf of federal, state or local candidates. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">46 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Disclosure is consistent with public policy, in the best interest of the
company and its shareholders, and critical for compliance with federal ethics laws. Moreover, the Supreme Court&#146;s <I>Citizens United</I> decision recognized the importance of political spending disclosure for shareholders when it said
&#147;[D]isclosure permits citizens and shareholders to react to the speech of corporate entities in a proper way. This transparency enables the electorate to make informed decisions and give proper weight to different speakers and messages.&#148;
Gaps in transparency and accountability may expose the company to reputational and business risks that could threaten long-term shareholder value. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Apple contributed at least $584,000 in corporate funds since the 2002 election cycle. (CQ:&nbsp;http://moneyline.cq.com/pml/home.do and National Institute on Money in State Politics:
http://www.followthemoney.org/index.phtml.) </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">However, relying on publicly available data does not provide a
complete picture of the Company&#146;s political expenditures. For example, the Company&#146;s payments to trade associations used for political activities are undisclosed and unknown. In many cases, even management does not know how trade
associations use their company&#146;s money politically. The proposal asks the Company to disclose all of its political spending, including payments to trade associations and other tax exempt organizations for political purposes. This would bring
our Company in line with a growing number of leading companies, including Microsoft, Merck and Prudential that support political disclosure and accountability and present this information on their websites. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s Board and its shareholders need complete disclosure to be able to fully evaluate the political use of
corporate assets. We urge your support for this critical governance reform. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Company&#146;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal
No.&nbsp;6 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;6. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company agrees with the proponent that transparency and accountability in corporate spending on political activities are important
and healthy corporate governance practices. The Company disagrees, however, that Proposal No.&nbsp;6 is necessary to achieve those objectives. The Company not only substantially implements the measures sought in Proposal No.&nbsp;6, but it goes even
further in its Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy. The Company believes its current practices exceed the practices followed by the corporate examples set forth by the proponent and demonstrate innovation in both contribution policy and
transparency. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The proponent requests that the Company report its policies and procedures for political contributions and
expenditures. The Company already discloses its Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy on its website at www.apple.com/investor. The Company makes all of its political contributions and expenditures in accordance with this policy.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The proponent also requests that the Company disclose its contributions and expenditures for or against any candidate for
public office and those used in any attempt to influence the general public, or segments thereof, with respect to elections or referenda. As stated in the Company&#146;s Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy, the Company does not make
political contributions to individual candidates. Any other political donation made by the Company will be reported publicly on the Company&#146;s website on an annual basis. Furthermore, the Company does not have a political action committee. In
all respects, the Company complies with all applicable laws and regulations governing political contributions and expenditures and discloses all political contributions and expenditures as required by law. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The proponent also seeks information on &#147;the title(s) of the persons in the Company who participated in making the decisions to make
the political contribution or expenditure.&#148; As disclosed in the Company&#146;s Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy, the Company&#146;s Government Affairs group, with the approval of the
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">47 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
Chief Executive Officer, makes all political contributions and expenditures on behalf of the Company. The proponent further requests that the report it seeks be presented to the Board of
Directors&#146; audit committee or other relevant oversight committee. Again, as provided in the Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy, management reports all political contributions and expenditures to the Board on an annual basis.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In its Supporting Statement, the proponent claims that &#147;the Company&#146;s payments to trade associations used for
political activities are undisclosed and unknown&#148; and that &#147;[i]n many cases, even management does not know how trade associations use their company&#146;s money politically.&#148; It is unclear what form of enhanced disclosure the
proponent aims to obtain when it appears to believe that the Company&#146;s management does not know how trade associations use the funds received from the Company. In fact, the Company does not allow trade association dues to be used to make
political donations. As required by the Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy, management reports the Company&#146;s membership and participation in trade organizations to the Board annually when it reports on its other political
activities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company belongs to various trade associations that focus on matters concerning the Company&#146;s interests,
such as combating piracy, promoting enforcement of intellectual property rights, advancing industry product standards and similar endeavors that benefit the Company and its customers. Some of the major trade associations to which the Company belongs
include TechAmerica, the Business Software Alliance, the Consumer Electronics Association, and Information Technology Industry Council. In keeping with the Political Contributions and Expenditures Policy, the Company does not join trade groups as a
way to influence elections. Indeed, the Company occasionally disagrees with political positions taken by the trade organizations to which it pays dues, and therefore public disclosure of the Company&#146;s payments to trade associations would not
necessarily reflect the Company&#146;s views. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As the foregoing demonstrates, the Company provides ample disclosure regarding
its participation in the political process, including its political contributions and expenditures, and complies with all applicable laws and regulations governing political contributions and expenditures. For all of these reasons, the Board
recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Vote Required </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposal No.&nbsp;6 requires the affirmative vote of (i)&nbsp;a majority of the shares present or represented by proxy and voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;a majority of the shares
required to constitute the quorum. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;6. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>PROPOSAL NO. 7 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Shareholder Proposal Entitled &#147;Adopt a Majority
Voting Standard for Director Elections&#148; </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has been advised that the California Public Employees&#146;
Retirement System (&#147;<I>CalPERS</I>&#148;), Legal Office, P.O. Box 942707, Sacramento, California 94229-2707, a beneficial owner of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock having a market value in excess of $2,000, intends to submit the
proposal set forth below at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>RESOLVED</B>, that the shareowners of Apple Inc. (Company) hereby request
that the Board of Directors initiate the appropriate process to amend the Company&#146;s articles of incorporation and/or bylaws to provide that director nominees shall be elected in uncontested elections by the affirmative vote of a majority of the
shares represented and voting at a duly held meeting at which a quorum is present (which shares voting </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">48 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
affirmatively also constitute at least a majority of the required quorum). This majority voting standard will apply, as permitted by law for California corporations, when the number of nominees
does not exceed the number of directors to be elected. A plurality voting standard will apply when the number of nominees exceeds the number of directors to be elected. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>SUPPORTING STATEMENT: </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Is Board of Directors&#146;
accountability important to you? As a long-term Company shareowner, CalPERS is sponsoring this proposal because we think accountability is of paramount importance. The voting standard described in this proposal would provide shareowners with a
meaningful role in uncontested director elections, in contrast to the Company&#146;s current voting system that effectively disenfranchises shareowners when directors run unopposed. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s current rules allow a director nominee to be elected with as little as his or her own affirmative vote
because &#147;withheld&#148; votes have no effect. This makes it impossible to defeat director nominees who run unopposed. We propose a majority voting standard that allows a management nominee&#146;s reelection bid to be defeated by shareowners who
hold a majority of shares that are voted at the election meeting and that also constitute a majority of the quorum required for the meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For these reasons, more than 80% of the companies in the S&amp;P 500 have adopted a form of majority voting for uncontested director elections. We believe the Company should join this growing number by
adopting the majority voting standard permitted by law for California corporations. These rules end the term of an incumbent director not re-elected by the required majority of shares and quorum in an uncontested election. The term end date will be
90 days after the election, or earlier if the board fills the director&#146;s seat or the director resigns before this 90 day period lapses. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Majority voting empowers shareowners to say &#147;no&#148; to unopposed directors. Incumbent board members serving in a majority vote system are aware that shareowners&#146; votes determine whether the
director remains in office. The power of majority voting, therefore, is not just to remove underperforming directors, but also to heighten director accountability through potential loss of majority support. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">CalPERS believes that the Company&#146;s shareowners will substantially benefit from increased accountability of
incumbent directors and from the power to reject directors who shareowners believe are not acting in their best interests. We view these as essential components of corporate governance standards that are closely related to financial performance. We
therefore ask you to join us in requesting the Company to adopt this proposal&#146;s majority voting standard for uncontested director elections. Please vote FOR this proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Company&#146;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;7 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;7. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board is committed to sound corporate governance policies and
practices. The Board carefully considered CalPERS&#146;s proposal and believes that it is not in the best interest of the Company and its shareholders, both for reasons of law and governance policy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The unusual mechanics of California law create the risk that directors who enjoy overwhelming shareholder support may fail to be elected
because an insufficient number of shareholders voted in the election. In addition, dissatisfied shareholders can make their voices heard in a number of ways ranging from correspondence with the Board to recall elections and alternative candidate
nominations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under CalPERS&#146;s proposal, in an uncontested election, the Company&#146;s directors would be elected by the
affirmative vote of a majority of shares represented and voting at a meeting rather than by the current plurality </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">49 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
voting standard. However, in making this proposal, CalPERS does not take into account the effects of California law concerning majority voting, which differs substantially from the law of
Delaware and other states, and presents a layer of complexity that makes the proposal particularly challenging to effectively implement for California companies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For most companies incorporated in states other than California, &#147;majority voting&#148; means that, in an uncontested election, a director must obtain more &#147;For&#148; votes than
&#147;Withheld&#148; in order to be elected. Under California&#146;s statutory majority vote requirement, however, election of a director requires not only the affirmative vote of a majority of the shares represented and voting at the meeting, but
also the affirmative vote of more than half of the shares required for a quorum for the meeting, which equals just over 25% of the outstanding shares. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Applying this standard would mean that even if there were no &#147;Withheld&#148; votes with respect to a director, and thus no indication of any shareholder disapproval, that director would still fail to
be elected if he or she did not obtain the affirmative vote of more than 25% of the outstanding shares. The Company could therefore lose its directors simply because too few shareholders cast their votes. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the past, this was not a significant concern. Brokers had &#147;discretionary voting authority&#148; to cast votes in uncontested
elections when their clients failed to provide them with voting instructions. Companies, whether applying plurality voting or majority voting, could expect that a sufficient number of votes would be cast, no matter what the outcome. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Recently, however, the stock exchanges implemented rule changes eliminating broker discretionary voting authority in director elections
when a client did not provide voting instructions. Now, because brokers may not vote those shares, the number of affirmative votes that companies can expect to be cast in director elections will be lower than before these rule changes. While this
may not make a difference in Delaware and other states that do not impose a &#147;majority of the required quorum&#148; standard, any company adopting the California majority voting standard risks the possibility that one or all of the
Company&#146;s directors will fail to be elected simply because too few shareholders failed to supply voting instructions to their brokers&#151;even if those shareholders were in favor of the directors. Each year, a significant number of the
Company&#146;s shareholders have failed to provide voting instructions to their brokers. In the Company&#146;s last annual meeting, over 175&nbsp;million shares were not voted by brokers with respect to the election of directors. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Thus, the Board believes that if the Company were to adopt the California majority voting standard, the combination of California&#146;s
unusual majority voting rules and the elimination of broker discretionary voting in director elections could make it significantly more difficult for a director to be elected even when shareholders are satisfied with that director and would prefer
that he or she be elected. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Further complexity arises from California&#146;s &#147;mandatory termination&#148; rule for
companies who choose to adopt the majority voting standard. The corporate laws of Delaware and other states permit companies to implement majority voting policies that require a director who does not meet that company&#146;s majority vote standard
to submit a resignation and allow the Board to accept or reject that resignation. California, on the other hand, mandates that a director&#146;s term in office end no later than 90 days after the determination of voting results if the director does
not obtain the required votes. Thus, the director&#146;s term will end regardless of whether a successor has been qualified, nominated and appointed and regardless of whether it is in the best interests of the Company and its shareholders. As a
result, if one of the Company&#146;s directors failed to receive sufficient votes, California law would force the Board to choose among three unsatisfactory alternatives, none of which may be in the interests of the Company and its shareholders. The
first would be to reappoint the same director to the Board, and thus to appear to be disregarding the shareholder preferences expressed in the voting outcome. The second would be to appoint a replacement, which would require the Board to identify,
interview, investigate and appoint a candidate with the appropriate qualifications, talent and expertise&#151;all within 90 days. This may well prove impossible given the Company&#146;s desire to appoint only the very best Board candidates. The
third alternative would be to allow the vacancy to remain unfilled until a suitable candidate is appointed. Even a small number of </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">50 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
vacancies, however, could seriously impair the Company&#146;s obligation to comply with NASDAQ listing standards, including the requirements for maintaining independent directors and directors
with particular qualifications or expertise. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Not only do the mechanics of California law make a majority voting standard
unreasonable, but the Company&#146;s own governance documents make adopting the standard unnecessary. CalPERS&#146;s claims that the Company&#146;s current voting system effectively disenfranchises shareholders are incorrect and misleading. Separate
from the director election process, the Company&#146;s shareholders have always had the ability to remove directors with or without cause for any reason, including to express dissatisfaction with a particular director. Further, any shareholder who
is dissatisfied with a director has always had the ability to nominate an alternative board candidate for shareholder consideration. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company believes its shareholders are satisfied with the composition of its Board and the Company&#146;s financial performance, as all of the Company&#146;s directors have consistently been elected by
the affirmative vote of substantially more than a majority of its outstanding shares. The Company has a strong corporate governance process designed to identify and propose director nominees who will best serve the interests of the Company and its
shareholders. The Board maintains a Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee that is composed entirely of independent directors, and all of the members of the Board, other than the Company&#146;s CEO, are independent. The Nominating and
Corporate Governance Committee applies a rigorous set of criteria in identifying director nominees and has established procedures to consider and evaluate persons recommended by shareholders. As a result of these practices, the Company&#146;s
shareholders have consistently elected highly qualified directors from diverse business backgrounds. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For all of the reasons
above, the Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Vote Required </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposal No.&nbsp;7 requires the affirmative vote of (i)&nbsp;a majority of the shares present or represented by proxy and
voting at the Annual Meeting and (ii)&nbsp;a majority of the shares required to constitute the quorum. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Recommendation of the Board
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board recommends a vote AGAINST Proposal No.&nbsp;7. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>OTHER MATTERS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company knows of no other matters to be submitted to the shareholders at the Annual Meeting. If any other matters properly come before the shareholders at the Annual Meeting, it is the intention of
the persons named on the proxy to vote the shares represented thereby on such matters in accordance with their best judgment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Dated:
January&nbsp;9, 2012 </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">51 </FONT></P>
